('additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function:misc:207355a5', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function', '8.1 The Gradient Function', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> The derivative of \\( -7 \\) is \\( -7 \\)</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A constant has gradient 0. A weak answer copies the constant down; a strong answer writes 0 — the term disappears.</p>", "question": "Differentiate the constant \\( -7 \\).", "options": ["\\( 0 \\)", "\\( -7 \\)", "\\( -7x \\)", "\\( 7 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Any constant differentiates to 0."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function:misc:f1799194', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function', '8.1 The Gradient Function', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \\( y = x^2 + 5 \\) differentiates to \\( 2x + 5 \\)</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The constant \\( +5 \\) goes to 0. A weak answer keeps it; a strong answer writes \\( \\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x \\).</p>", "question": "Differentiate \\( y = x^2 + 5 \\).", "options": ["\\( 2x \\)", "\\( 2x + 5 \\)", "\\( 2x + 1 \\)", "\\( x + 5 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The constant \\( +5 \\) differentiates to 0, leaving \\( 2x \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function:misc:a950e08b', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function', '8.1 The Gradient Function', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> For a table with points either side of \\( x \\), a forward difference is the best gradient estimate</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> When symmetric data is available the central difference is more accurate. A weak answer grabs one side; a strong answer uses both sides so the point is the midpoint.</p>", "question": "Values at \\( x = 3, 4, 5 \\); best estimate of the gradient at \\( x = 4 \\)?", "options": ["Central, using \\( x = 3 \\) and \\( x = 5 \\)", "Forward, using \\( x = 4 \\) and \\( x = 5 \\)", "Backward, using \\( x = 3 \\) and \\( x = 4 \\)", "Use \\( x = 4 \\) only"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x = 4 \\) is the midpoint of 3 and 5, so the central difference is most accurate."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function:misc:fbb42837', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function', '8.1 The Gradient Function', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> The chord gradient IS the gradient of the curve at the point</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A finite chord only estimates it. A weak answer treats them as equal; a strong answer notes the chord gradient approaches the tangent gradient as \\( h \\to 0 \\), and shrinking \\( h \\) improves the estimate.</p>", "question": "How do you make a chord gradient a better estimate of the tangent gradient?", "options": ["Use a smaller interval \\( h \\)", "Use a larger interval \\( h \\)", "Give more significant figures", "Use only one point"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "A smaller (and symmetric) interval brings the chord closer to the tangent."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function:tips:9c5b9cc7', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function', '8.1 The Gradient Function', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Show the working for a numerical gradient", "reading": "<p>For a numerical-gradient part, the method mark is earned by writing the <strong>difference quotient</strong> in full before evaluating: \\( \\dfrac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1} \\). Substitute the actual table values, e.g. \\( \\dfrac{3.1447 - 1.5358}{1.8 - 1.4} \\), then give the answer. A bare number with no visible calculation risks the method mark.</p>", "question": "How do you secure the method mark on a numerical-gradient question?", "options": ["Write the difference quotient with the table values before evaluating", "Write only the final number", "Round to 1 significant figure", "Differentiate the curve algebraically and substitute the given x-value"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The M mark is for the visible \\( \\frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1} \\) calculation using the given values."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function:tips:3c1bc0be', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function', '8.1 The Gradient Function', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Which difference should you use?", "reading": "<p>Choose by looking at the data. If the target \\( x \\) is the <strong>midpoint</strong> of two values, use the <strong>central</strong> difference — it is the most accurate. If the values are <strong>not symmetric</strong> about the target (as with Ben''s \\( x = 1.2 \\) and \\( 1.8 \\) about \\( 1.4 \\)), a \"central\" calculation actually estimates the gradient at the wrong point, so you must use a one-sided (forward or backward) estimate instead.</p>", "question": "Why can''t Ben use \\( x = 1.2 \\) and \\( x = 1.8 \\) for the gradient at \\( x = 1.4 \\)?", "options": ["The intervals are unequal, so 1.4 is not the midpoint", "The values are too large", "1.8 is not on the curve", "You may only subtract y-values that are next to each other in the table"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 1.4 \\) is not halfway between \\( 1.2 \\) and \\( 1.8 \\) (that midpoint is \\( 1.5 \\)), so the estimate would be the gradient at the wrong place."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function:tips:9964dc64', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:8-1-the-gradient-function', '8.1 The Gradient Function', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Differentiate cleanly, term by term", "reading": "<p>Work down the polynomial one term at a time: <strong>multiply by the power, reduce the power by 1</strong>, carry any coefficient through, and send every constant to 0. Writing each term''s result keeps errors to one mark. Remember the guardrail: only whole-number powers — no fractions, surds, trig or \\( a^x \\).</p>", "question": "Differentiate \\( y = 4x^3 - 2x + 9 \\).", "options": ["\\( 12x^2 - 2 \\)", "\\( 12x^2 - 2 + 9 \\)", "\\( 12x^2 - 2x \\)", "\\( 4x^2 - 2 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 4x^3 \\to 12x^2 \\), \\( -2x \\to -2 \\), constant \\( +9 \\to 0 \\): \\( 12x^2 - 2 \\)."}'::jsonb),
